<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: FIRST DAY OF SCHOOL IS A BUMMER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK, Erma Bombeck is on vacation. She left a few of her favorite 
columns behind. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The first day of school is rough on mothers -- especially the young ones who 
are saying goodby to an era. I dropped in on Jean Carp to hold her hand and 
reassure her that everyone would survive the day. 
</P>
<P>
"Did you get Kenny off to school?" I asked. 
</P>
<P>
"Yes, finally," she groaned, pouring herself a cup of coffee. 
</P>
<P>
"What happened?" 
</P>
<P>
"He didn't want to go." 
</P>
<P>
"You're kidding." 
</P>
<P>
"No, he said the kids wouldn't like him." 
</P>
<P>
"Didn't you tell him how ridiculous that was?" 
</P>
<P>
"Yes, I told him how during the summer he had made a lot of friends. Then he 
said his teachers had it in for him." 
</P>
<P>
"Why would he say a thing like that when he doesn't even know them yet?" 
</P>
<P>
"I don't know. I almost got him out of the door when he came back and changed 
his clothes for the third time. Said his belt was too wide and his shoes too 
clean." 
</P>
<P>
"Oh, good grief." 
</P>
<P>
"That's when he slumped down into a chair and said, 'I'll never find the 
restroom or the cafeteria. I'm surely not going to ask someone.' " 
</P>
<P>
"What did you tell him?" 
</P>
<P>
"I told him I'd put a note in his pocket with B-O-Y-S printed on it and pack 
his lunch." 
</P>
<P>
"Did that do it?" 
</P>
<P>
"Nope. He wanted to know how many days he had to put in until Christmas 
vacation." 
</P>
<P>
"What an attitude," I said, shaking my head. 
</P>
<P>
"He got out to the driveway. Then he came back in again and said, 'Why do I 
have to go to school anyway? Why can't I just stay home and help you? I could 
run errands and take out the garbage and watch the baby for you when you go to 
the dentist.' Can you believe he actually offered to get a regular job?" 
</P>
<P>
"Incredible." 
</P>
<P>
"I really felt sorry for him, though," said Jean. "When I watched him walk down 
the street clutching his lunch bag and hanging onto those pitiful few books and 
a new pencil, I wanted to call him back. But when a man is 44 years old and the 
new principal, he has no choice." 
</P>
<P>
I shook my head. "Don't be surprised if he bolts at lunch." 
</P>
</TEXT>
