<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: UCSD WOMEN WIN TITLE IN VOLLEYBALL TOURNAMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The UC San Diego women's team won the championship of the Labor Day Volleyball 
Festival by defeating Cal Poly Pomona, 16-14, 15-12, in the final at University 
High School in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
Elizabeth Tan, an all-tournament team selection, Vikki Van Duyne and Dana 
Simone combined for 21 kills in the final match for UCSD (8-0). 
</P>
<P>
UCSD had earlier defeated Western New Mexico, Cal Baptist and Humbolt State to 
finish 6-0 in pool play, then beat Cal State Los Angeles, 16-14, 15-12, in the 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
Point Loma Nazarene College (5-2) was eliminated after losing to CSLA, 12-15, 
15-11, 15-11, in the opening round of the championship bracket. PLNC had 
earlier defeated Mount St. Mary's and Alaska and lost to Cal Poly Pomona. PLNC 
setter LeAnne Lopez also was named to the all-tournament team. 
</P>
<P>
MEN'S SOCCER 
</P>
<P>
USIU won its season opener, defeating Grand Canyon College, 2-1, at USIU. The 
Gulls trailed, 1-0, at halftime but got goals from sophomore Noel Pekel and 
junior John Molomo in the final 22 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
The University of San Diego scored three goals in the first half en route to a 
4-0 victory over Cal State Bakersfield at the USD Soccer Complex. Paul Gelvezon 
scored two goals and Alex Stricek and Phillip Button each had one for USD 
(2-0). The Toreros, who have not been scored upon this season, allowed just 
three shots. 
</P>
<P>
SWIMMING 
</P>
<P>
Jamshid Khajavi, 36, of San Marcos became the first person this year to 
complete the swim from Catalina Island to the mainland, according to a member 
of his support crew. 
</P>
<P>
The support crew member, Jack Robertson of San Diego, said Khajavi completed 
the 18-mile swim in 16 hours, 12 minutes, arriving at Point Vincent near Long 
Beach shortly before 1 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
Khajavi, a native of Iran who is now a U.S. citizen, endured seven-foot waves 
and high winds through the first 5 1/2 hours and later encountered two large 
sharks, Robertson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
