<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLACH TAKES A WALK, SHOWN THE GATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ken Flach, who walked off the court at the U.S. Open Saturday in the third set 
of his first-round mixed doubles match with partner Patty Fendick, was fined 
$3,200, defaulted from the competition and also defaulted from the men's 
doubles with partner Robert Seguso. 
</P>
<P>
Flach left the court with his team trailing Elise Burgin and Laurie Warder, 
5-2. Apparently upset over a series of line calls, Flach twice slammed tennis 
balls off the court, then walkedaway. 
</P>
<P>
Grand Slam supervisor Ken Farrar fined Flach $350 for each instance of ball 
abuse, $1,500 for failing to complete the match and $1,000 for defaulting the 
match. 
</P>
<P>
Farrar also automatically defaulted Flach and Seguso from the men's doubles, 
which they won in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
